segments.text: over by the campus theater.
And I really don't know how I got my business messed up, but I did terribly.
First of all, my grades were terrible.
And secondly, I got to bumming around with some upperclassmen in other units.
And I'm going to say that they led me wrong on whatever
And I turned up having a clash of personalities with my first sergeant.
And it got rather serious.
They had what they called rams at that time.
A little book about the book of rams looked like a set of three to five note cards.
And another class would write you some rams.
thought you deserved such.
My first son thought I deserved a bunch of them.
I think I set an indoor record for RAM.
It led to my acquiring the name of Head.
You want to hear that story?
Yes, yes.
I can't believe this is thrilling, but I had a grandfella in my outfit named Buckwires.
What a great guy he was.
And he was a San Antonio boy.
Went to Central Catholic over and came to A&M.
He was a senior when I was a freshman, which made him class of 42.
But for whatever reason it was, he laid over and became a five-year man.
And bear in mind that a senior was somebody that you spoke to with care, you held in great reverence, and the only thing above a senior
was a five-year man.
Weiss was still taking military science and that type of thing.
But I ran into all this trouble with his first son, who incidentally was a good guy, but what a class of personality.
Anyway, Buck said to his first son, anything, to paraphrase,
I'll have a talk with Davis and I'll straighten him out.
From now on, you leave him alone, I'll take him over.
So he got me in a room on the third floor, I'm going to say room 14.
And he, nobody there but us.
He told me, he said, now the first sergeant has turned you over to me.
You're my responsibility from now on.
And I think that you'll be gone from here before long because I think
We're all going to run you off.
He said, someday, if you do stay around, since you may be a junior or a senior or even a five-year man like me, he said, someday, you might have a gold hat card and you might get to wear boots.
But he said, you've got to bear in mind that if I tell you that wall's pink, it's pink.
Remember this.
like it was yesterday.
And he said, whatever else I tell you, that's the gospel.
And he said, it doesn't make any difference if you do become a singer.
He said to me, you ain't never going to be anything but a pisshead.
And that was only what number of years ago?
Summer of 1942.
And somebody heard that, I guess, or he repeated it to them, and they mercifully
deleted the prefix and I became known as Head and it's endured quite well.
Buck Wires, a great guy.
Memorable teachers, advisors, other non-student individuals that had an important effect on your life?
Who were some of the outstanding
Oh, mercy.
I was in such terrible trouble up until World War II as a student at Texas A&M.
I had, of course, the usual number of professors and they were all smart and they were all good.
I just didn't listen carefully.
As a matter of fact, I would have never graduated from Texas A&M, I'm quite sure, had not World War II occurred.
The government mobilized 16 million people so I could get out of A&M.
Because before the war, I was in every school they had.
But every time I turned around, I was meeting up with chemistry.
And I was just out of it.
Just absolutely out of it.
After the war, it was a different story.
Who was your chemistry teacher?
Oh, Dr. Potter.
Dr. Potter.
I'm sorry, Dr. Potts.
He had a son.
As a matter of fact, the psychiatrist, Devin Bryan, I'm not sure that he's still here, but Dr. Potts.
Did he have a nickname?
I can't recall that he did.
The other famous chemistry professor over there was Heddy N. Jones.
He did have it.
Later became a client of mine and his family.
Now what was his nickname?
Hed N. Jones.
Do you know why that?
Why that head end came?
I do not know.
He would come into class and he would say, in regard to the next meeting of this class, it depends on how Mrs. Jones treats me.
If she bakes me a cherry pie, you probably won't have a quiz.
But if she doesn't make me a cherry pie, you're probably going to have a quiz.
I knew him well and
in later years.
What about English?
Oh, there was some of the famous names.
Talk about those.
There was Shaky Powell.
Seemed like to me he taught me some type of public speaking and he had a remarkable voice.
He made fun or ridiculed Aggies to an extent respectfully.
He said, you think you can yell loud for A&M athletes greatness on Kyle feet?
He said, listen to this.
And he had something about his voice that he could make the walls crumble.
I remember that very well, very vividly.
And as I recall, that was shaky power.
And so he could make the walls shake.
With that voice.
You have to do it.
And that's exactly what we need.
To modulate his voice.
I remember well, he said, now listen to this.
You learn to do that, and you make some noise and kind of think.
There was Square Root Jackson.
He taught mathematics.
Didn't teach me much, but he was a mathematics guy.
And probably a single man.
I know as late as 1963 when I moved back to Bryan, he was still riding them.
bicycle down Texas Avenue and you didn't want to do that even in 1963.
He used to come in a classroom and approach the blackboard with an eraser and he would take a couple of minutes and would erase that board symmetrically.
Very precise.
It was a beautiful thing when he finished.
Then he would take that eraser and he would dust it across the back of a chair.
And then he would hold it at eye level
and drop it two or three times on the floor, pick it up and drop it again.
I had an old classmate, Bobby Harris, down in Abasota.
He one day said, hey, Ruth, how come you dropped the racer like that?
And he said, Mr. Harris, someday I'm going to turn it loose and it won't fall.
And Mr. Harris didn't have any future in trigonometry after that.
Great old gentleman.
There was a fellow named Dutch Halpern who was a brilliant mathematician.
I don't know whether he's been mentioned to you or not, but he was top of the line in the mathematics department at the time.
And, of course, you heard him screaming Allen Elson.
Describe him.
Oh, he was...
I can remember him saying, I have spent nine years in the college classroom preparing to teach.
And when he taught, you could hear him all over the campus.
That's the name...
I knew him well in later years after moving back to Bryan.
What did he scream about?
Of course he was teaching history because I remember South American history I think perhaps was his specialty.
But did he have some special likes or dislikes?
That I can't recall.
I probably wasn't listening good enough.
Who else?
Oh, Mercy.
Dr. Cofer was a well-known fellow around on the campus.
His son, D. Brooks Cofer, Jr., still in Bryan, fine lawyer.
Dr. Cofer was an English fellow.
Seemed like to me he was called Dusty, but I'm not sure.
I never had him.
But he gave me some very interesting pamphlets fit for the archive of Texas A&M.
I knew him, and he was a grand old general.
In later years, a fellow that didn't impress me or help me along in courses after the war was a fellow named Satch Elkins.
I'm thinking of those that have got these nicknames.
Why Satch?
I can't recall.
I don't know that one either.
I don't know, but he was a business professor.
But he was, E.W.
was his initial rider called, but he was notoriously known in sacks everywhere.
Another industry one was Homer Hill Norton, who was a football coach.
Well respected, a member of the college football hall of fame.
He was called by his ball player, Hoghead, for H.A.
Wasn't that creative?
I can't remember that there are others.
There are bound to be.
Okay.
One of them, I do remember a statistician named Miles Hamilton.
You know, this was the era of nicknames.
Now, were those nicknames put-downs, or were they, in fact, backhanded compliments?
Backhanded compliments in every instance, I would say.
I think so, too.
A lot of my classmates, a lot of my acquaintances, some older, had nicknames.
We had a fellow that we called Wampajaw first.
Notoriously known.
That Buck Weirson one.
Got an old friend here in College Station now.
His initials were FC, so he was called Flatcock.
And known quite well.
Catfish Winters.
Shorty Fuller.
Dog Dawson.
Jelly Stein.
Not everybody, but many had nicknames.
I don't know that children knew that anymore.
All right, now on a serious note, if you turned to someone for advice and counsel, particularly when you came back after the war, who was it?
After the war?
Either one, but I was meaning don't leave that era out.
If I had a problem prior to, and I lived with problems,
My battery commander before the war, as I said, was Jack Taylor and Tudor Ball.
They were very, very nice guys and great gentlemen, great soldiers.
And you could go, a freshman could go to them with a problem.
You could not go to the sophomore class with a problem.
You did not want to see those people.
That's just...

just the way it was but it had a good some good points not many but some good one of them was you were obligated to know everybody in your dormitory and and almost literally their hometown and their course of study which meant not very many places could i be in texas that i don't know somebody unless they did i did know somebody
And that was part of the deal.
After the war, Lord, I was an old man by then, as everybody else was.
I was 22 years old, something like that.
And I was dead serious then.
I made up my mind to be a lawyer.
Dead serious.
And whereas I made all C's and D's and F's before the war, I made all A's after the war.
That's the only way I got into law school, with a C after.
All right, now we won't get to that war, those things in a minute.
What were the expected rules of classroom behavior and attendance and so forth for you before you go away to the war?
Well, you weren't going to miss any classes.
The upperclassmen saw that.
We did not miss classes.
And I don't ever recall any disturbance in the classroom of any kind or any place else.
Sophomores handled all that.
Whereas you got Bob White and 150 policemen now, you had a sophomore class that could handle that discipline.
That presented no problem.
No problem.
Did you go to sleep in class?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I did some of them.
Got a hot foot one time.
I got literally the only hot foot I've ever had.
I got a hot foot at the Rural Socialist Clinic.
Dr. Dan Davis was teaching it, and I am almost sure that he never missed a beat.
He was giving his lecture and didn't intend to be interrupted by a hot foot, and it almost killed him.
And I did scream out, never missed a beat.
Summer of 42.
Let's see, YMCA, did it have a, what happened at that building?
What role did that building play in a student's life?
Well, there were two.
One was called the old Y building that still stands.
It's right out the west door of the academic building, right across the street from the old Y's law and puryear halls.
I guess they're now gone.
The Cavalry Regiment had a rich heritage in those two buildings, I'll tell you.
But the old Y was operated by a fellow named Cashin, Red Cashin's father.
I can't recall his initials.
Probably M.L.
Red's Mason Lee, and he's probably Mason Lee Jr.
I knew Mr. Cashin casually, knew who he was.
Seemed like to be in the bottom of the old Y.
there was a small bowling alley.
Can't be sure about that.
I am positive that in the bottom of the old wine was a small confectionery that was operated by Bill Sparks and J.F.
Casey.
Again, Bill Sparks and J.F.
Casey sat on a high stool and took in nickels and dimes and a fortune.
You get a sandwich there if you had the money and get an ice cream cone.
And there were a couple reading rooms upstairs
It seemed like.
I'm sure the Y must have conducted some probably very good and native programs.
I was never in on any of them because I was busy over in the new area.
Then there was a new Y.
The new Y was, I believe, a stucco building right at the extreme northwest corner of the block occupied by the 12 dormitories called the new area.
And they had a pool table in there and not much else.
They did have a radio because I heard President Roosevelt's speech to the Congress in that building on that radio.
Hold that one because that's important.
Guyon Hall.
Oh, Guyon Hall.
What happened in Guyon Hall?
They showed you a picture.
It might have charged a quarter there.
What other events happened in Gine Hall?
Oh, they bring different things there.
Freshmen would get to see some of them.
Now, could you go to a movie any night you wanted to?
I remember attending a religious activity in Gine Hall.
What kind?
Some speaker who was here for, let's say, two or three days.
Religious emphasis week, maybe?
Perhaps, perhaps.
Guy Hall was famous for another thing.
What's that?
Well, he had a basement.
Not really a basement.
He had an underneath area.
And when the upperclassmen left here in the spring, you could store a footlocker under there.
And you had to get out on your stomach to crawl around almost to find these footlockers.
And one of the chores of a new freshman was to get under the building and find his warden master's
Foot Locker.
And you met a lot of good fellows under there with the same chore you did.
Do you remember any important personalities, nationally famous people that came to visit the campus?
To visit the campus?
Like Roosevelt didn't come?
He came here before I was around, probably in 1939 maybe.
But Garner didn't come and John J. Pershing didn't come.
I remember after the war now, there was an outstanding man, General Eisenhower, spoke at the muster in 1946 in Kyle Field.
Describe that.
Well...
I get goofy every now and then.
No, no.
That's what we want.
Well, it was a great time.
And the reason it was a great time is because it was April the 21st.
Surely I'm correct about that.
And not everybody, but nearly everybody was back from World War II.
And the campus was
swarming with folks you had known before the war.
Not all of them were in school on that very day, but they came everywhere to hear General Eisenhower.
And it was well known, well publicized.
It was a big time event.
General Eisenhower, as I recall, had been very generous about praise
Anyway, it was a big deal.
Did he say anything special about Aggies?
I can't recall, but he had to be complimentary.
I can't recall.
I was there.
Before the war, do you remember going to Muster's?
No.
I've often thought about that.
It may be that on an old

dark as I remember wet day at the evening formation retreat in 1942 it seemed to me that a number of names were called out none of which I could hear they were doing this down around Duncan Hall and I've often thought that maybe that was a muster but
I'm not sure that it was.
The first musket I recall in my own experience was at Camp Ruber, Oklahoma in 1943.
What camp?
Camp Ruber.
Ruber.
Let's see.
Before the war, now, were still silver taps.
Where and what was it?
Yeah, I remember silver taps vividly.
Do it the same way.
You assembled in front of the academic building and they came out on the portico, is that what I wanted to say?
Balcony up there.
And... Who went?
I assumed everybody.
I certainly did.
Lord, if I got to go, everybody went.
And how did you behave afterward?
After TAPS is over,
I have no clear memory, but I can't imagine that you did anything except slink away to your hole.
I think that's good.
Let's see.
Other student organizations other than the Corps before the war.
Bands, singing cadets, anything?
Describe those.
Well, I would say to you that undoubtedly,
student government as it is known now is terribly different than what the situation was then.
The student life business was in the Corps of Cadets.
Everybody, with few exceptions, were in the Corps of Cadets.
If you were a bad 4F person or a slight handful of graduate students,
you might not belong to the Corps.
But other than that, everybody belonged to the Corps, and you had about all the student life you could have with what went on in your military unit.
Now, I can remember that many towns.
I can remember that Wichita Falls, my hometown, had a Wichita Falls hometown club.
And what did those hometown clubs do?
Oh, Lord, we did meet.
I got to go a time or two.
One thing we did, I can recall, this was a before-the-war event, was we brought the Aggieland Orchestra to Wichita Falls during the Christmas season.
They made a big tour over many spots in Texas over that period, and one stop was in Wichita Falls, a big dance.
What was the Aggieland Orchestra?
Was this a symphony?
Oh, yes, it was a symphony.
There's a fellow named Curly Brown.
headed that deal up.
My friend Buck Wires played the drums and sang way on the outskirts of town.

And an old classmate of mine who was a freshman, very unusual for a freshman to be in an Angolan orchestra, but he happened to be a good sax man and we called him Fish Angolan Murphy because he was a member of the band.
A boy named Dinkle Webb played something
Freddie Nelson, who still lives in Bryan today, played at my 50th wedding anniversary in February.
Was the piano man?
Oh, let me think.
Don Hackney played a saxophone.
This was a band.
Something else I need to mention about them, too.
This was a band who played popular tunes of the day.
The significant thing about it is, I suppose,
It was in the spring or summer of 1942 that they played on the Fitch Bandwagon.
The Fitch Bandwagon was a network radio program whereby college bands came to perhaps New York.
It certainly wasn't Waxahachie.
It was Chicago, New York, or wherever.
And that was their program for that day.
It was a tremendous event on A&M campus.
All of the windows were open.
You didn't have a radio.
You heard the radio.
Who was the director of that?
Curly Brown was our student.
Oh, yeah.
All of them were students.
Oh, yeah.
And they played for dances if they didn't have some big-time guy coming in.
Now, do you remember any of the big-time groups that did come?
Oh, yeah.
Who?
There was a fella named, I guess, Jimmy.
Jimmy Lunsford.
He was a big-time deal.
Carmen Caballero.
Got to be others because the regimental balls and the senior ring dance, that was big-time stuff.
Now, where were those dances held?
Sabisa Hall.
Describe them.
Describe the dances?
Well, the girls came from everywhere.
And the girls came out from Bryan.
They were known as the Bryan 400.
And the girls came from Denton, from, I don't know if that was still CIA or TSCW or what at the time.
They came on buses and so on.
Like her?
How did the dance participants dress?
Girls had on nice forms.
And you could wear tuxedos.
If you didn't have tuxedos, a tuxedo, you wore a dress uniform.
Dresses that you hate, the best dress you hate.
And what kind of behavior pattern was there at those?
There was very little ruckus on the inside.
It was quite tame.
There was always some activity elsewhere.
That was a big late Dayton time.
You could find out, could I have a late Dayton?
That meant after her main man took her home, you could pick her up and so on.
And it'd be some visiting of the local joints, of which there wasn't too many, but so on.
What were those local joints?
Oh, I could talk a day about that.
Is this going on longer than you want it to go?
No, no, no.
And if we don't finish today, we'll come back another day at your convenience.
Do you understand that I slept on my head last night?
You've got a stiff neck.
I've got a stiff neck.
I guess the most famous joint was Ed's, Uncle Ed's, which was on the Wellman Road within walking distance of the campus.
famous old gentleman out there, his name was Hartlicker, Ed Hartlicker.
And he had a daughter, Marilyn, who courted Jack Fugate, who was the winner of the Ugly Man contest at the time.
They still do.
Lord have mercy, I can't think of his wife.
Anyway, Arnold Ed's.
It was a famous place.
You would take a girl there.
There'd be no trouble.
There was just a lot of beer drinking that went on, to be real.
What were the favorite brands of beer that Aggies considered?
Oh, I would suppose there were two that come to mind.
There might have been others, but certainly Grand Prize was in the heyday at the time, and Southern Select, and Jack's,
I don't remember Bud being particularly popular.
It had to exist, but I don't recall it.
Did you dance at Uncle Ed's?
Little.
Did you eat?
A little, not much.
It was a beer joint for kids.
Was there any kind of rule that you remember about age in order to buy beer?
Lord have mercy, it couldn't have been much because I came here at 16.
And was there a problem with drunkenness?
Some of those little A&M boys wouldn't get kind of drunk, but it wasn't a problem.
First of all, you didn't have any automobiles.
An automobile was the exception.
I had 32 times 2 is 64 plus 16 times 2 is 32.
I had 100 men in my unit.
And as I recall, it was one automobile.
There was an old boy named Lee Ravey from Amarillo.
He was a little bit advanced in age.
He was probably a year old to be a senior and so on.
And he had a car.
So you weren't going to be a DWI very often.
All right.
Other than hard liquors, what were some other famous places?
Well...
